entry.title: Coastal Flood Warning issued September 22 at 7:45PM EDT until September 23 at 4:00PM EDT by NWS Wakefield VA
entry.summary:
* WHAT...For the Coastal Flood Warning, one to two feet of inundation above ground level in low-lying areas near shorelines and tidal waterways. For the Beach Hazards Statement, dangerous rip currents.
* WHERE...In North Carolina, Eastern Currituck County. In Virginia, Virginia Beach.
* WHEN...For the Coastal Flood Warning, until 4 PM EDT Monday. For the Beach Hazards Statement, through Monday evening.
* IMPACTS...Widespread flooding of vulnerable areas will result in an elevated threat of property damage to homes and businesses near the waterfront and shoreline. Breaking waves of 4 to 5 ft will result in rough surf conditions and a high risk of rip currents.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued September 22 at 12:24PM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF MODERATE TO HEAVY RAINFALL IS APPROACHING SOUTHEAST ALASKA FROM THE WEST WITH THE FIRST SIGNIFICANT RAINFALL ARRIVING SUNDAY NIGHT. PREVIOUS FORECASTS HAVE FOCUSED ON THE POTENTIAL FOR HEAVY RAIN OVER THE SOUTHERN PANHANDLE. HOWEVER, LATEST MODE DATA INDICATES THAT THE CENTRAL AND NORTHERN PANHANDLE WILL ALSO EXPERIENCE MODERATE TO HEAVY RAIN WITH AMOUNTS AS MUCH OR MORE THAN EXPECTED FOR THE SOUTHERN ZONES.
AT PRESENT, RAINFALL ON SUNDAY NIGHT APPEARS TO BE THE HEAVIEST FOR THIS MULTI-DAY EVENT WITH ACCUMULATIONS AS HIGH AS 1.5 INCHES BY MONDAY MORNING. LESSER AMOUNTS ARE FORECAST FOR MONDAY THROUGH TUESDAY NIGHT. RAINFALL RATES SUCH AS THIS ARE CONSIDERED NORMAL FOR THIS TIME OF THE YEAR AND ARE NOT CONSIDERED TO BE EXCESSIVE. THIS IS, HOWEVER, THE FIRST SIGNIFICANT RAINY PERIOD OF THE FALL SEASON AND MAY COME AS A SURPRISE TO SOME. RIVERS, CREEKS, AND STREAMS WILL RESPOND TO THIS MUCH RAINFALL, WITH MORE FLASHY STREAMS RESPONDING THE MOST WITH TONIGHT'S RAINFALL. AT THIS TIME, NO FLOODING IS EXPECTED.
MOST WINDY CONDITIONS WILL OCCUR TONIGHT AS WELL WITH SUSTAINED WINDS OF 15 TO AS MUCH AS 20 MPH IN INLAND LOCATIONS WITH GUSTS AS HIGH AS 30 TO 35 MPH NEAR COASTAL LOCATIONS ON THE INNER CHANNELS AND OUTER COAST.
KEEP UP WITH CURRENT CONDITIONS AND FORECAST UPDATES DURING THIS EVENT AT WEATHER.GOV/JUNEAU.
